PART VII
SURVIVAL AND PROLIFERATION
The Order distinguishes between survival as suffering (mere endurance, hoping for rescue) and survival
as proliferation (thriving in place, becoming native to the condition). The Order teaches the second. The
wasteland is not an enemy to be endured — it is a territory to be learned, a teacher to be honored, a
garden waiting to be tended.
WATER — First Priority
Rain collection, groundwater, surface water (requires treatment), atmospheric condensation, plant
sources, solar stills. Purification: boiling (10 min rolling boil), distillation, filtration
(cloth/sand/charcoal), UV, iodine/chlorine short-term. Multiple small containers, rotate storage, protect
from light.
""Water is life. Life finds water. I am life. I will find water.""
FOOD — Second Priority
Foraging (know 100% before consuming), insects (high protein, safe if cooked), trapping and snaring
(passive, efficient), container gardening, hydroponics, seed saving. Preservation: drying, smoking,
salting, fermenting, root cellaring. Ethics: take only what you need, use all of what you take, give
thanks.
""The wasteland feeds those who know how to ask. I am learning to ask.""
SHELTER — Third Priority
Site selection: water access, drainage, wind protection, sun exposure, defensible. Types: debris hut
(quick, warm), tarp shelter, lean-to, wickiup (thatch frame), earth-sheltered (permanent), cave. Thermal
regulation through insulation, thermal mass, fire, and shared body heat.
""I carry my home in my skills. Wherever I stop, I can build what I need.""
FIRE — Fourth Priority
Methods for redundancy: friction (bow drill, hand drill), flint and steel, ferro rod, magnifying lens,
battery and steel wool. Uses: cooking (makes food safer), water purification, warmth, protection, signal,
community gathering. Fire draws people together — it is as social as it is practical.
""Fire is the first technology. I remember how to call it.""
MEDICINE — Integrated with all levels
